@startuml Public Access via Cloudflare Tunnel
!theme plain
title Exposing Local k3s Service Publicly (Cloudflare Tunnel)

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA

actor "External User\n(any network)" as user

cloud "Cloudflare Edge\n(global anycast network)" as cf #Orange {
  component "Cloudflare DNS\n(your-domain.com → Cloudflare)" as cfdns
  component "Cloudflare Proxy\n(handles TLS, DDoS, firewall)" as cfproxy
  component "Tunnel Connector\n(receives cloudflared connection)" as cfconnector
}

node "Windows Host" as windows #LightCyan {

  node "WSL2 Ubuntu" as wsl #LightBlue {

    package "Cloudflare Agent" as cfagent #LightYellow {
      component "cloudflared daemon\n(outbound connection only)\nno open ports needed" as cloudflared
    }

    node "k3s CLUSTER (1 node)" as k3s #LightSkyBlue {

      package "Built-in Add-ons" as addons #Lavender {
        component "Klipper / ServiceLB\n(:80 on localhost)" as klipper
        component "Traefik\n(Ingress controller)" as traefik
      }

      package "Namespace: my-app" as ns #White {
        component "Ingress\n(path rule /)" as ing
        component "Service\n(ClusterIP)" as svc
        component "Pod\n(my-service:v1)" as pod1
        component "Pod\n(my-service:v1)" as pod2
      }
    }
  }
}

' --- Tunnel setup (outbound) ---
cloudflared -[#blue]-> cfconnector : outbound tunnel\n(QUIC / HTTP2)\ncloudflared initiates this

' --- External traffic flow ---
user -[#red]-> cfdns             : https://your-domain.com
cfdns -[#red]-> cfproxy          : DNS resolves to Cloudflare IP
cfproxy -[#red]-> cfconnector    : proxied through Cloudflare edge
cfconnector -[#red]-> cloudflared : routed through tunnel
cloudflared -[#red]-> klipper    : http://localhost:80

' --- Internal k3s flow ---
klipper -[#orange]-> traefik
traefik -[#orange]-> ing
ing -[#orange]-> svc
svc -[#green]-> pod1             : load balance
svc -[#green]-> pod2             : load balance

note right of cfconnector
  Cloudflare manages the
  public endpoint. No router
  or firewall config needed.
  Works behind NAT.
end note

note right of cloudflared
  Install inside WSL2:
  curl -L https://github.com/cloudflare/cloudflared/releases/latest/download/cloudflared-linux-amd64 -o cloudflared
  chmod +x cloudflared
  mv cloudflared /usr/local/bin/

  Quick tunnel (no domain needed):
  cloudflared tunnel --url http://localhost:80

  Named tunnel (custom domain):
  cloudflared tunnel login
  cloudflared tunnel create my-tunnel
  cloudflared tunnel route dns my-tunnel your-domain.com
  cloudflared tunnel run my-tunnel
end note

note top of cf
  Cloudflare handles:
  - Free TLS/HTTPS automatically
  - DDoS protection
  - Stable public URL
  - No dynamic IP problem
  - No open ports on router/firewall
end note

note bottom of windows
  ** ADVANTAGES over Port Forwarding **
  - No router config needed
  - No firewall rules needed
  - WSL2 IP changes don't matter
  - Free HTTPS out of the box
  - Stable URL even if public IP changes

  ** REQUIREMENTS **
  - Cloudflare account (free)
  - A domain added to Cloudflare
    (OR use trycloudflare.com for
     zero-config quick tunnels)
end note

@enduml